      "date": "2013-09-14 01:25:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/c073e5b2-1cd7-11e3-9961-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b9ae0aa268751f44ea1427d0aa951ace0e6a603d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-09-14 20:56:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/cb2bd2b8-1d71-11e3-9f81-52540035b04c).  Ran 20 tests.  6 tests failed: sanity-quota, insanity, conf-sanity, replay-single, sanityn, sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b7d82b95b1103d7207e9eddb8698cb986a7fc63c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-01 23:56:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWhat is the intended use of this option?  The configured system that is left over after testing finishes depends on the test being run, in particular conf-sanity will change and reformat the filesystem several times. Instead of using \"auster -K\" you could just run the test directly and/or run llmount to get a configured filesystem?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ea5f71527f94164b0e90f520e4413c7b72cabb64",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 278,
        "name": "Nathaniel Clark",
        "email": "nclark@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "utopiabound"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-04 13:12:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe purpose of this patch is to allow auster to leave a setup in place after running a test (for example after it run with --only)  This is just a way to be lazy and not need to run llmount before running auster.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "1949be588e67157babbc06eb0ad557472b3c8562",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 198,
        "name": "Minh Diep",
        "email": "mdiep@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "mdiep"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-04 15:53:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPlease try this\n./llmount.sh\n./auster ...\n\nverify that lustre is still mounted. I believe it is.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c691c8f03491057b17a2e49f36425870e1ea1e18",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 278,
        "name": "Nathaniel Clark",
        "email": "nclark@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "utopiabound"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-08 13:28:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Abandoned",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    }
